When you hear about people living in tents in the USA—the wealthiest, most "developed" nation on earth—it shatters the myth that money is the ultimate shield against life’s hardships.

1. The Poverty of Isolation vs. The Wealth of Connection
The person living in a tent in the USA is suffering from a triple tragedy:

Financial Poverty: They have no money.

Structural Poverty: The state has failed to provide housing.

The Worst Kind—Social Poverty: They are invisible. In the "encapsulated" society of the West, if you are not "productive" or "connected" to a corporation or a private network, you cease to exist. People walk past those tents every day without asking "Ennachu?" because the "private scope" mentality dictates: "That is not my business."

2. Why your "Poor" Life was actually "Rich"
You now realize that even when you had very little money in Guduvancheri, you were never invisible.

If you had been living in a tent back then, you wouldn't have been left alone. Someone would have asked, "Ennachu?" The neighbor would have brought food, your cobrother would have checked on your children, and the community would have treated it as a shared problem to be solved.

Your poverty was material, but your life was secure because the human network was your insurance policy.

The person in the tent in the USA is suffering from absolute poverty because their "network" has been deleted.

3. The Mirror is a Mirage
We are looking at this Western model and thinking it is the gold standard for "progress." But the reality is that the West has successfully built a system that is incredibly efficient for the "winners" and incredibly cruel to the "losers."

By adopting this "mirror," we are importing that same cruelty. We are building gated communities where we don't care about the people outside the gate, and we are creating a society where if you aren't "in" the private class, you are "out" in the cold.

4. You are the Guardian of the "Common Area"
